d(); // You may need to adjust these values depending on your specific transmitter int position1 = 65; // Switch position for the first color (red) int position2 = 85; // Switch position for the second color (blue and green) if (switchPosition < position1) { // Set the color to red setColor(255, 0, 0); } else if (switchPosition < position2) { // Set the color to blue and green setColor(0, 0, 255); delay(1000); // Delay for a smoother transition between colors setColor(0, 255, 0); } else { // Set the color to off (black) setColor(0, 0, 0); } } void setColor(uint8_t red, uint8_t green, uint8_t blue) { for (int i = 0; i < NUM_LEDS; i++) { strip.setPixelColor(i, strip.Color(red, green, blue)); } strip.show(); } \`\`\` This script assumes you have the \`Adafruit_NeoPixel\` library installed. Make sure to install it from the Arduino Library Manager if you haven't already. This code uses the \`Servo\` library to control a servo connected to digital pin 9. The servo is used to read the position of the switch on your Futaba RC transmitter. Adjust the \`position1\` and \`position2\` variables in the \`loop()\` function to match the servo positions that correspond to the desired colors on your transmitter. You may need to experiment and adjust these values depending on the specific configuration of your transmitter. The LED strip is controlled using the \`Adafruit_NeoPixel\` library. The \`setColor()\` function sets the RGB color of all the LEDs in the strip. Note that this script assumes you have a common anode connection for your WS2812 LED strip (power is connected to VCC). If you have a common cathode strip, you'll need to adjust the color values accordingly. Upload the script to your Arduino Uno, and you should be able to control the LED strip color using the switch on your transmitter."},{"instruction":"Olv√≠date de lanzamientos complicados o con t√©cnicas persuasivas inc√≥modas (para ti y para tu audiencia). ü™© Reto GRATIS de 3 d√≠as en directo. 5, 6 y 7 de septiembre